                <h2>Case Scene: $15,000 Monthly Budget, No Clue If Money Was Well Spent</h2>
<p>Zhang's team runs a home storage products business in Shenzhen. They built an independent website at the beginning of the year and burned $15,000 in advertising in the first month. End of month accounting showed: Facebook ROI 1.8, Google Ads ROI 2.3, TikTok video ROI only 0.9. What puzzled him most was that while Facebook's overall data looked acceptable, half of the ad creatives were losing money, while two breakout products ran out of budget mid-day because limits were too restrictive.</p>
<p>This wasn't a problem of how much budget, but how it was allocated.</p>
<hr />
<h2>Problem 1: Channel Budget Allocation Based on Gut Feeling</h2>
<h3>Diagnostic Criteria</h3>
<p>Many teams allocate budgets by "feeling which channel works better." But the problems are:</p>
<ul>
<li>User decision cycles vary significantly across channels</li>
<li>Traffic quality fluctuates with timing</li>
<li>Concentrated spending on a single channel easily hits a ceiling</li>
</ul>
<h3>Action Taken</h3>
<p>Zhang later changed to this approach: look at each channel's historical cost per acquisition (CPA) first, then make elastic adjustments based on seasonal trends.</p>
<p><strong>Practical Allocation Reference (Home Products Category, $15,000 Monthly Budget):</strong></p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Channel</th>
<th>Percentage</th>
<th>Amount</th>
<th>Strategic Focus</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Meta (Facebook + Instagram)</td>
<td>45%</td>
<td>$6,750</td>
<td>Retargeting + breakout creative scaling</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Google Ads (Search + Shopping)</td>
<td>30%</td>
<td>$4,500</td>
<td>Precision keywords + product catalog ads</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>TikTok</td>
<td>15%</td>
<td>$2,250</td>
<td>Short video seeding + UGC testing</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Reserve Testing Fund</td>
<td>10%</td>
<td>$1,500</td>
<td>New channel/creative validation</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<hr />
<h2>Problem 2: Campaign-Level Budget Locked Down</h2>
<h3>Diagnostic Criteria</h3>
<p>Each campaign had a daily limit of 200-300 RMB. Breakout creatives ran out of budget by afternoon, while underperforming creatives kept burning. This indicates: <strong>budget allocation wasn't stratified by performance</strong>.</p>
<h3>Action Taken</h3>
<p>Adjusted to a three-tier budget mechanism:</p>
<p><strong>① Testing Tier (10% of total budget)</strong><br />
- Daily budget: test 3-5 new creatives<br />
- Bidding strategy: manual bidding, control cost per click<br />
- Goal: find new creatives with CTR &gt; 1.5%, CVR &gt; 3%</p>
<p><strong>② Main Tier (60% of total budget)</strong><br />
- Daily budget: dynamically adjusted based on actual consumption of validated creatives<br />
- Bidding strategy: lowest cost or priority cost<br />
- Goal: stable spend, maintain ROAS ≥ 2.5</p>
<p><strong>③ Breakout Tier (30% of total budget)</strong><br />
- Daily budget: breakout creatives get unlimited or high ceiling<br />
- Bidding strategy: cost cap mode to protect margins<br />
- Goal: scale for GMV, but set daily spend alerts</p>
<hr />
<h2>Problem 3: Retargeting Budget Ignored</h2>
<h3>Diagnostic Criteria</h3>
<p>Customer acquisition cost for new visitors is often 5-7 times that of returning customers, but many teams put all budget on new customer acquisition, dragging down overall ROI.</p>
<h3>Action Taken</h3>
<p>Zhang later mandated: <strong>at least 20% of each channel's budget must go to retargeting</strong>.</p>
<ul>
<li>Cart abandoners: reach within 7 days, creative focused on limited-time discounts</li>
<li>Visitors who didn't convert: retarget within 14 days, emphasize product differentiation</li>
<li>First-time buyers: promote related categories or accessories within 30 days</li>
</ul>
<hr />
<h2>Results After Three Months</h2>
<table>
